{"title_page": "Ali in the Quran", "text_new": "The majority of [[Islam]]ic commentators do not believe that [[Ali ibn Abi Talib]] is explicitly mentioned in the [[Quran]]. An exception is in [[Abu Abdullah Ja'far ibn al-Aswad ibn al-Haytham|Ja'far Ibn al-Haytham]]'s ''Kitab al-Munazarat'', there is a specific mention of the words ''\u02bfAliyyan'' ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u064b\u0651\u0627}}), ''\u02bfAliyyun'' ({{lang|ar|\u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u064c\u0651}}) and ''\u02bfAlayya'' ({{lang|ar|\u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u064e\u0651}}) in the [[Quran]] which, he believes, according to grammatical rules are the names to [[Ali]]. Examples of these, he says, are the following verses: ''In the (mother of the Book which is with Us, he is Ali, full of wisdom'';<ref>[http://tanzil.net/#43:4 Quran, 43:4]</ref> ''We appointed for them Ali as a voice of truth'';<ref>http://tanzil.net/#19:50 Quran, 19:50]</ref> and ''This is the straight path of Ali''.<ref>[http://tanzil.net/#15:41 Quran, 15:41]</ref><ref name=\"Leaman\"/> However, many other verses of the Quran have been interpreted, by both Shia and Sunni scholars, as referring to Ali.\n\n== Chapters and verses ==\n\n=== Verse 2:207 ===\n{{main|Laylat al-Mabit}}\n\nLaylat al-Mabit is the night when the [[Prophets and messengers in Islam|Islamic prophet]] [[Muhammad]] left the city of [[Mecca]] and began his [[Hijra (migration)|migration]] to [[Medina]]. Many of the Meccan polytheists had planned to kill Muhammad on the night that he left Mecca. That night, Ali risked his life by sleeping in Muhammad's bed so that Muhammad could leave Mecca safely. When the polytheists of Mecca went to Muhammad's room with the aim of killing him, they instead found Ali in his bed.\n\nThe 207th [[Ayah|verse]] of [[Surat al-Baqarah]] in the [[Quran]] is interpreted as having been revealed in this regard to show the sacrifice of [[Imam]] 'Ali for saving the life of the Islamic Prophet:<ref name=\"Tabataba'i, Al-Mizan\">{{citation |author=Tabataba'i |title=Al-Mizan |volume=2 |page=135}}</ref><ref name=\"Nishapuri, Al-Mustadrak\">{{citation |author=Nishapuri, Al-Hakim |author-link=Al-Hakim Nishapuri |title=Al-Mustadrak |volume=3 |page=5}}</ref><ref name=\"Shaybani, FAS\">{{citation |author=Shaybani |title=Fada'il al-sahaba |volume=2 |page=484}}</ref><ref name=\"'Ayyashi, Tasir\">{{citation |author='Ayyashi |title=Tafsir |volume=1 |page=101}}</ref><ref name=\"Zarkashi, Al-Burhan\">{{citation |author=Zarkash\u012b |author-link=Badr Ad-Din az-Zarkashi |title=Al-Burh\u0101n f\u012b `ul\u016bm al-Qur\u2019\u0101n |volume=1 |page=206}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|And of ''an-n\u0101s'' ({{lang-ar|\u0671\u0644\u0646\u064e\u0651\u0627\u0633}}, the people) is he who sells his ''nafs'' ({{lang-ar|\u0646\u064e\u0641\u0652\u0633}}, self), seeking the ''mar\u1e0d\u0101till\u0101h'' ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u064e\u0631\u0652\u0636\u064e\u0627\u062a\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0644\u0647}}, approval of [[God in Islam|God]]). And [[Allah|All\u0101h]] is ''[[Names of God in Islam#List of names|Ra\u02be\u016bfum-bil-\u02bfib\u0101d]]'' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u064e\u0621\u064f\u0648\u0652\u0641\u064c \u0628\u0650\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0639\u0650\u0628\u064e\u0627\u062f}}, Kind to the servants).|Qur'an|{{cite quran|2|207|b=n}}}}\n\n=== Verse 3:61 ===\n{{main|Event of Mubahala#Verse of Mubahalah}}\n\nIn the year 10 [[Islamic calendar|AH]] (631/32 CE), a Christian envoy from [[Najran]] (now in southwestern [[Saudi Arabia]]) came to Muhammad to debate doctrines regarding [[Jesus in Islam|\u02bf\u012as\u0101]] ([[Jesus]]). After Muhammad likened Jesus' miraculous birth to the creation of [[Islamic view of Adam|\u0100dam]] ([[Adam]]),{{efn|[http://tanzil.net/#3:59 Quran, 3: 59]}}\u2014who was born to neither a mother nor a father \u2014 and when the Christians did not accept the Islamic doctrine about Jesus, Muhammad was instructed to call them to [[Event of Mubahala|Mubahalah]] where each party should ask God to destroy the false party and their families.<ref>{{harvnb|Momen|1985|pp=13\u201314}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Madelung|1997|pp=15\u201316}}</ref><ref name=\"Madelung 16\">{{harvnb|Madelung|1997|p=16}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>{{Cite quran|3|61| quote=But whoever disputes with you in this matter after what has come to you of knowledge, then say: Come let us call our sons and your sons and our women and your women and our near people and your near people, then let us be earnest in prayer, and pray for the curse of Allah on the liars.}}</blockquote>\n\nMany historians, both Shi'ite and Sunni, state that the people that Muhammad brought to the Mubahalah were Ali, [[Fatimah]], [[Hasan ibn Ali|Hasan]], and [[Husain Ibn Ali|Husain]]. Accordingly, in the [[Event of Mubahala#Verse of Mubahalah|verse of Mubahalah]], it has been stated the phrase \"our sons\" refers to Hasan and Husayn, \"our women\" refers to Fatimah, and that \"ourselves\" refers Muhammad and Ali.<ref name=\"Leaman\">{{cite book|last=Leaman|first=Oliver|author-link=Oliver Leaman|title=The Quran: an Encyclopedia|date=2006|publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]] e-Library|isbn=978-0-415-32639-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/quranencyclopedi2006unse/page/28 28\u201331]|url=https://archive.org/details/quranencyclopedi2006unse/page/28}}</ref><ref name=\"Madelung 16\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Momen|1985|p=14}}</ref><ref name=\"mavani\" />\n\n=== Chapter 5 ===\n{{main|Al-Ma'ida}}\n\n==== Verse 5:3 ====\n{{main|Verse of Ikmal al-Din}}\n\nIn the Shi'ite version of the [[Farewell Sermon]], immediately after Muhammad had finished [[The event of Ghadir Khumm#The sermon|his sermon]] at Ghadir Khumm, the following verse of the Quran was revealed:<ref>{{cite book|last1=al-Bahrani|first1=Seyyed Hashim|title=Al-Burhan Fi Tafsir al-Quran|volume=1|pages=434\u2013437|title-link=Al-Burhan Fi Tafsir al-Quran}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Makarem Shirazi|first1=Naser|title=Tafsir Nemooneh|volume=4|pages=263\u2013271|title-link=Tafsir Nemooneh}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Sobhani|first1=Ja'far|title=Al-Iman va al-Kofr fi al-Ketab va al-Sunnah|volume=1|page=244}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>This day have those who reject faith given up all hope of your religion: yet fear them not but fear Me. This day have I perfected your religion for you, completed My favour upon you, and have chosen for you Islam as your religion (5:3).</blockquote>\n\n==== Verse 5:55 ====\n{{main|The verse of Wilayah}}\n\n<blockquote>{{Cite quran|5|55| translator=    s| quote= Only Allah is ''Waliyyukum'' ({{lang-ar|\u0648\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u064f\u0651\u0643\u064f\u0645}}, \"your ''Wal\u012b''\" (masculine, plural tense)) and His Messenger and those who believe, those who keep up prayers and pay ''az-Zak\u0101h'' (the Poor-rate) while they bow.        \n}}</blockquote>\n\nShi'ite scholars, along with Sunni ones such as Tabari,{{efn|See at-Tabari: at-Tarikh, vol.6, p.186}} [[Al-Suyuti]]{{efn|See as-Suyuti: [[Dur al-Manthur]], vol.2, pp. 293\u20134}} and [[Fakhr ad-Din ar-Razi|Razi]],{{efn|See ar-Razi: at-Tafsiru 'l Kabir, vol.12, p.26}} recorded{{efn|See also az-Zamakhshari: at-Tafsir al-Kashshaf, vol.1, p.469; al-Jassas:Ahkamu 'l-Quran, vol.2, pp. 542\u20133; al-khazin: at-Tafsir, vol.2, p.68 Imamate: The vicegerency of the Holy Prophet By Sayyid Saeed Akhtar Rizv p24 }} that one day, when Ali was performing the [[Salat|ritual prayers]] in the [[Prophet's Mosque|Mosque]], a beggar began to ask for [[alms]]. Ali extended his finger, and the beggar removed his ring.<ref name=\"Rizvi1988\">{{cite book|author=Akhtar Rizvi, Sayyid Saeed|title=Imamate: The vicegerency of the Holy Prophet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0f2qAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA24|year=1988|publisher=Bilal Muslim Mission of Tanzania|isbn=978-9976-956-13-9|pages=24\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"CornilleConway2010\">{{cite book|author1=Cornille, Catherine|author2=Conway, Christopher|title=Interreligious Hermeneutics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZpcNBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT124|date=1 July 2010|publisher=Wipf and Stock Publishers|isbn=978-1-63087-425-4|pages=124\u2013}}</ref> Then Muhammad observed this, and a passage of the Qur'an was sent down upon him (5:55),<ref name=\"Rizvi2014\">{{cite book|author=Hasnain Rizvi, Syed Tilmiz|title=Fazail-e-Ali ibn Abi Talib|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kx9uBgAAQBAJ&pg=RA1-PA42|date=3 February 2014|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1-304-87140-4|pages=1\u201342}}</ref> According to Shi'ites, in this verse, \"obedience is absolute and conjoined with obedience to God and his messenger\", so the person identified as ''Wali'' must be infallible.<ref name=\"mavani\">{{cite book|last1=Hamid|first1=Mavani|title=Religious Authority and Political Thought in Twelver Shi'ism|pp=68\u201373|date=2013|publisher=New York and London: Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-62440-4}}</ref>\n\n[[Abu Dhar al-Ghifari]], one of the earliest converts to Islam, was said to have related the following [[hadith|\u1e25adith]] to [[Ahmad ibn Muhammad al-Tha'labi]], the [[Sunni]] author of the ''[[Tafsir al-Thalabi]]'':{{sfnp|Shomali|2004|pp=140\u2013142}}\n<blockquote>One day, I was praying with [[Muhammad in Islam|the Prophet]] in the mosque when a beggar walked in. No one responded to his pleas. The beggar raised his hands towards the heavens and said, \"[[Allah]]! Be a witness that I came to the [[Prophet's Mosque]] and no one gave me anything.\" Imam Ali ([[Peace be upon him (Islam)|a]]) was bowing during his prayer at that time. He pointed his little finger, on which was a ring, towards the beggar who came forward and took away the ring. The incident occurred in the Prophet's presence, and he raised his face towards heaven and prayed:<blockquote>\"O Lord! my brother [[Moses in Islam|Musa]] had begged of Thee to open his breast and to make his work easy for him, to loosen the knot of his tongue so that people might understand him, and to appoint from among his relations his brother, as his ''wali'', and to strengthen his back with [[Aaron|Harun]] and to make Harun his partner in his work. O Allah! Thou said to Musa, 'We will strengthen thy arm with thy brother. No one will now have access to either of you!'<ref>{{cite quran|20|25|36|style=ref}}.</ref> O Allah! I am Muhammad and Thou hast given me distinction. Open my breast for me, make my work easy for me, and from my family appoint my brother Ali as my ''wali''. Strengthen my back with him.\"{{sfnp|Shomali|2004|pp=140\u2013142}}{{sfnp|Rizvi & al.|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=0f2qAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA24 24]}}</blockquote></blockquote>\n\n==== Verse 5:67 ====\n{{main|The verse of announcement}}\n\n<blockquote>{{Cite quran|5|67| translator=    s| quote=O Messenger! deliver what has been revealed to you from your Lord; and if you do it not, then you have not delivered His message, and Allah will protect you from the people; surely Allah will not guide the unbelieving people.}}</blockquote>\n\nThis verse urges the Prophet of Islam to [[the event of Ghadir Khumm|announce Ali as his successor]] on his way from his last pilgrimage to Mecca.<ref name=\"EncyclopediaIslam\">{{cite encyclopedia|last1=Vaglieri |first1=Laura Veccia |authorlink=Laura Veccia Vaglieri |title=G\u0332h\u0332ad\u012br K\u0332h\u0332umm|encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia of Islam, Second Edition |year=2012 |accessdate=11 October 2019 |publisher=Brill Online |url=http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-2/ghadir-khumm-SIM_2439| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n=== Verse 33:33 ===\n{{main|The verse of purification}}\n\n<blockquote>{{Cite quran|33|33| translator=    s| quote= And stay in your houses and do not display your finery like the displaying of the [[Jahiliyyah|Ignorance]] of yore; and keep up the Salah, and pay the Zakah, and obey Allah and His Messenger. Allah only desires to keep away the uncleanness from you, ''[[Ahl al-Bayt|Ahlal-Bayt]]'' (People of the House), and purify you a (thorough) purifying.      \n}}</blockquote>\n\nShi'ite commentators, along with some Sunni ones, record that the ''people of the house'' in this verse are the [[Ahl al-Kisa|Ahl al-Kis\u0101\u02be]] (People of the Mantle): Muhammad, Ali, Fatimah, Hasan and Husayn.<ref name=\"Leaman\"/><ref name=\"mavani\" /><ref>Sahih Muslim, ''Chapter of virtues of companions, section of the virtues of the Ahlul-Bayt of the Prophet,'' 1980 Edition Pub. in Saudi Arabia, Arabic version, v4, p1883, Tradition #61</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Muhammad ibn Jarir al-Tabari |title=Tafsir al-Tabari |volume=XXII |pages=5\u20137}}</ref><ref name=\"iranicaonline\">[http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/al-e-aba-the-family-of-the-cloak-i H. Algar, \"Al-E Aba,\" Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica, I/7, p. 742; an updated version is available online at http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/al-e-aba-the-family-of-the-cloak-i (accessed on 14 May 2014).]</ref><ref>\"F\u0101\u1e6dima.\" Encyclopaedia of Islam, Second Edition. Edited by: P. Bearman, Th. Bianquis, C.E. Bosworth, E. van Donzel, W.P. Heinrichs. Brill Online, 2014. Reference. 08 April 2014</ref>{{efn|see also al-Bahrani, Ghayat al-Marum, p. 126:al-Suyuti, al-Durr al-Manthur, Vol. V, p.199; Ahmad ibn Hanbal, al Musnad, Vol. I, p.331; Fakhr al-Din al-Razi, al-Tafsir al-Kabir, Vol. I, p.783; Ibn Hajar, al-Sawa'iq p.85 }}\nAccording to [[Wilferd Madelung]], \"the great majority of the reports quoted by al-Tabari in his commentary on this verse support this interpretation.\"{{efn|See Tabari, Jarir XXII, 5\u20137.}}{{efn|Madelung writes \"the verse addressed to the wives of the Prophet: 'Stay in your houses, and do not show yourselves in spectacular fashion like that of the former time of ignorance. Perform the prayer, give alms, and obey God and His Messenger. God desires only to remove defilement from you, o people of the house (ahl al-bayt)^ and to purify you (yutahhirakum) completely' (XXXIII 33). Who are the 'people of the house' here? The pronoun referring to them is in the masculine plural, while the preceding part of the verse is in the feminine plural. This change of gender has evidently contributed to the birth of various accounts of a legendary character, attaching the latter part of the verse to the five People of the Mantle ahl al-kisa: Muhammad, Ali, Fatima, Hasan and Husayn.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Madelung|1997|pp=14\u201315}}</ref>}} However, [[Ibn Kathir]], in his tafsir of the verse, says \"the [Sunni] scholars are unanimously agreed that they ([[Muhammad's wives]]) were the reason for revelation in this case&nbsp;... but others may be included by way of generalization.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Tafsir Ibn Kathir|publisher=IslamKotob|page=126}}</ref>\n\n=== Verse 42:23 ===\n{{main|The verse of Mawadda}}\n\n<blockquote>{{Cite quran|42|23| translator=    s| quote= That is of which Allah gives the good news to His servants, (to) those who believe and do good deeds. Say: I do not ask of you any reward for it but ''al-mawaddah fil-qurb\u0101'' ({{lang-ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0648\u064e\u062f\u064e\u0651\u0629 \u0641\u0650\u064a \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0642\u064f\u0631\u0652\u0628\u064e\u0649}}, the love for the near relatives), and whoever earns good, We give him more of good therein; surely Allah is Forgiving, Grateful.        \n}}</blockquote>\n\nShi'ite commentators and Sunni ones like [[Al-Baydawi|Baydawi]]{{efn|See Baydawi, Anwar at-Tanzil. Vol.5 p.53<ref name=\"Momen 1985 334\">{{harvnb|Momen|1985|p=334}}</ref> }} and [[Fakhr ad-Din ar-Razi|Razi]]{{efn|See Razi, Mafatih al-Ghayb, vol. 7, pp. 273\u20135<ref name=\"Momen 1985 334\"/>}} agree that the near relatives in question are Ali, Fatimah, Hasan and Husayn.<ref>{{harvnb|Momen|1985|p=152}}</ref> Such a view is rejected by Ibn Kathir, who claims the verse refers to the [[Quraysh]], quoting [[hadith]]s from [[Sahih Bukhari]] and [[Ahmad ibn Hanbal]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Muhammad Saed Abdul-Rahman |title=The Meaning and Explanation of the Glorious Qur'an (Vol 9) |date=29 October 2009 |publisher=MSA Publication Limited|isbn=978-1-86179-667-7|page=40}}</ref> According to [[Wilferd Madelung|Madelung]] Shi'ite and Sunni sources agree that by the near relatives in this verse and other similar verses were meant the descendants of Muhammad's great-grandfather [[Hashim ibn Abd Manaf|Hashim ibn \u02bfAbd Manaf]], and of Hashim's brother [[Muttalib ibn Abd Manaf|Al-Mu\u1e6d\u1e6dalib]].<ref>{{harvnb|Madelung|1997|p=13}}</ref>{{verification needed|date=October 2016}}{{clarify|reason=Wouldn't this just be the descendants of Abd Manaf?|date=October 2016}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Islamic schools and branches]]\n* [[Muhammad in the Quran]]\n** [[Obedience Verse#Shia view|Verse of Obedience]]\n* [[Al-Farooq (title)]]\n* [[Schools of Islamic theology]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|2}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |first=Wilferd |last=Madelung |authorlink=Wilferd Madelung |title=The Succession to Muhammad: A Study of the Early Caliphate |year=1997 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=978-0-521-64696-3}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Momen |first=Moojan |authorlink=Moojan Momen |title=An Introduction to Shi'i Islam |year=1985 |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |isbn=978-0-300-03531-5}}\n\n[[Category:Quran]]\n[[Category:Ali]]\n", "text_old": "The majority of [[Islam]]ic commentators do not believe that [[Ali ibn Abi Talib]] is explicitly mentioned in the [[Quran]]. An exception is in [[Abu Abdullah Ja'far ibn al-Aswad ibn al-Haytham|Ja'far Ibn al-Haytham]]'s ''Kitab al-Munazarat'', there is a specific mention of the words ''\u02bfAliyyan'' ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u064b\u0651\u0627}}), ''\u02bfAliyyun'' ({{lang|ar|\u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u064c\u0651}}) and ''\u02bfAlayya'' ({{lang|ar|\u0639\u064e\u0644\u064e\u064a\u064e\u0651}}) in the [[Quran]] which, he believes, according to grammatical rules are the names to [[Ali]]. Examples of these, he says, are the following verses: ''In the (mother of the Book which is with Us, he is Ali, full of wisdom'';<ref>[http://tanzil.net/#43:4 Quran, 43:4]</ref> ''We appointed for them Ali as a voice of truth'';<ref>http://tanzil.net/#19:50 Quran, 19:50]</ref> and ''This is the straight path of Ali''.<ref>[http://tanzil.net/#15:41 Quran, 15:41]</ref><ref name=\"Leaman\"/> However, many other verses of the Quran have been interpreted, by both Shia and Sunni scholars, as referring to Ali.\n\n== Chapters and verses ==\n\n=== Verse 2:207 ===\n{{main|Laylat al-Mabit}}\n\nLaylat al-Mabit is the night when the [[Prophets and messengers in Islam|Islamic prophet]] [[Muhammad]] left the city of [[Mecca]] and began his [[Hijra (migration)|migration]] to [[Medina]]. Many of the Meccan polytheists had planned to kill Muhammad on the night that he left Mecca. That night, Ali risked his life by sleeping in Muhammad's bed so that Muhammad could leave Mecca safely. When the polytheists of Mecca went to Muhammad's room with the aim of killing him, they instead found Ali in his bed.\n\nThe 207th [[Ayah|verse]] of [[Surat al-Baqarah]] in the [[Quran]] is interpreted as having been revealed in this regard to show the sacrifice of [[Imam]] 'Ali for saving the life of the Islamic Prophet:<ref name=\"Tabataba'i, Al-Mizan\">{{citation |author=Tabataba'i |title=Al-Mizan |volume=2 |page=135}}</ref><ref name=\"Nishapuri, Al-Mustadrak\">{{citation |author=Nishapuri, Al-Hakim |author-link=Al-Hakim Nishapuri |title=Al-Mustadrak |volume=3 |page=5}}</ref><ref name=\"Shaybani, FAS\">{{citation |author=Shaybani |title=Fada'il al-sahaba |volume=2 |page=484}}</ref><ref name=\"'Ayyashi, Tasir\">{{citation |author='Ayyashi |title=Tafsir |volume=1 |page=101}}</ref><ref name=\"Zarkashi, Al-Burhan\">{{citation |author=Zarkash\u012b |author-link=Badr Ad-Din az-Zarkashi |title=Al-Burh\u0101n f\u012b `ul\u016bm al-Qur\u2019\u0101n |volume=1 |page=206}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|And of ''an-n\u0101s'' ({{lang-ar|\u0671\u0644\u0646\u064e\u0651\u0627\u0633}}, the people) is he who sells his ''nafs'' ({{lang-ar|\u0646\u064e\u0641\u0652\u0633}}, self), seeking the ''mar\u1e0d\u0101till\u0101h'' ({{lang|ar|\u0645\u064e\u0631\u0652\u0636\u064e\u0627\u062a\u0650 \u0671\u0644\u0644\u0647}}, approval of [[God in Islam|God]]). And [[Allah|All\u0101h]] is ''[[Names of God in Islam#List of names|Ra\u02be\u016bfum-bil-\u02bfib\u0101d]]'' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u064e\u0621\u064f\u0648\u0652\u0641\u064c \u0628\u0650\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0639\u0650\u0628\u064e\u0627\u062f}}, Kind to the servants).|Qur'an|{{cite quran|2|207|b=n}}}}\n\n=== Verse 3:61 ===\n{{main|Event of Mubahala#Verse of Mubahalah}}\n\nIn the year 10 [[Islamic calendar|AH]] (631/32 CE), a Christian envoy from [[Najran]] (now in southwestern [[Saudi Arabia]]) came to Muhammad to debate doctrines regarding [[Jesus in Islam|\u02bf\u012as\u0101]] ([[Jesus]]). After Muhammad likened Jesus' miraculous birth to the creation of [[Islamic view of Adam|\u0100dam]] ([[Adam]]),{{efn|[http://tanzil.net/#3:59 Quran, 3: 59]}}\u2014who was born to neither a mother nor a father \u2014 and when the Christians did not accept the Islamic doctrine about Jesus, Muhammad was instructed to call them to [[Event of Mubahala|Mubahalah]] where each party should ask God to destroy the false party and their families.<ref>{{harvnb|Momen|1985|pp=13\u201314}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Madelung|1997|pp=15\u201316}}</ref><ref name=\"Madelung 16\">{{harvnb|Madelung|1997|p=16}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>{{Cite quran|3|61| quote=But whoever disputes with you in this matter after what has come to you of knowledge, then say: Come let us call our sons and your sons and our women and your women and our near people and your near people, then let us be earnest in prayer, and pray for the curse of Allah on the liars.}}</blockquote>\n\nMany historians, both Shi'ite and Sunni, state that the people that Muhammad brought to the Mubahalah were Ali, [[Fatimah]], [[Hasan ibn Ali|Hasan]], and [[Husain Ibn Ali|Husain]]. Accordingly, in the [[Event of Mubahala#Verse of Mubahalah|verse of Mubahalah]], it has been stated the phrase \"our sons\" refers to Hasan and Husayn, \"our women\" refers to Fatimah, and that \"ourselves\" refers Muhammad and Ali.<ref name=\"Leaman\">{{cite book|last=Leaman|first=Oliver|author-link=Oliver Leaman|title=The Quran: an Encyclopedia|date=2006|publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]] e-Library|isbn=978-0-415-32639-1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/quranencyclopedi2006unse/page/28 28\u201331]|url=https://archive.org/details/quranencyclopedi2006unse/page/28}}</ref><ref name=\"Madelung 16\"/><ref>{{harvnb|Momen|1985|p=14}}</ref><ref name=\"mavani\" />\n\n=== Chapter 5 ===\n{{main|Al-Ma'ida}}\n\n==== Verse 5:3 ====\n{{main|Verse of Ikmal al-Din}}\n\nIn the Shi'ite version of the [[Farewell Sermon]], immediately after Muhammad had finished [[The event of Ghadir Khumm#The sermon|his sermon]] at Ghadir Khumm, the following verse of the Quran was revealed:<ref>{{cite book|last1=al-Bahrani|first1=Seyyed Hashim|title=Al-Burhan Fi Tafsir al-Quran|volume=1|pages=434\u2013437|title-link=Al-Burhan Fi Tafsir al-Quran}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Makarem Shirazi|first1=Naser|title=Tafsir Nemooneh|volume=4|pages=263\u2013271|title-link=Tafsir Nemooneh}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Sobhani|first1=Ja'far|title=Al-Iman va al-Kofr fi al-Ketab va al-Sunnah|volume=1|page=244}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>This day have those who reject faith given up all hope of your religion: yet fear them not but fear Me. This day have I perfected your religion for you, completed My favour upon you, and have chosen for you Islam as your religion (5:3).</blockquote>\n\n==== Verse 5:55 ====\n{{main|The verse of Wilayah}}\n\n<blockquote>{{Cite quran|5|55| translator=    s| quote= Only Allah is ''Waliyyukum'' ({{lang-ar|\u0648\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u064f\u0651\u0643\u064f\u0645}}, \"your ''Wal\u012b''\" (masculine, plural tense)) and His Messenger and those who believe, those who keep up prayers and pay ''az-Zak\u0101h'' (the Poor-rate) while they bow.        \n}}</blockquote>\n\nShi'ite scholars, along with Sunni ones such as Tabari,{{efn|See at-Tabari: at-Tarikh, vol.6, p.186}} [[Al-Suyuti]]{{efn|See as-Suyuti: [[Dur al-Manthur]], vol.2, pp. 293\u20134}} and [[Fakhr ad-Din ar-Razi|Razi]],{{efn|See ar-Razi: at-Tafsiru 'l Kabir, vol.12, p.26}} recorded{{efn|See also az-Zamakhshari: at-Tafsir al-Kashshaf, vol.1, p.469; al-Jassas:Ahkamu 'l-Quran, vol.2, pp. 542\u20133; al-khazin: at-Tafsir, vol.2, p.68 Imamate: The vicegerency of the Holy Prophet By Sayyid Saeed Akhtar Rizv p24 }} that one day, when Ali was performing the [[Salat|ritual prayers]] in the [[Prophet's Mosque|Mosque]], a beggar began to ask for [[alms]]. Ali extended his finger, and the beggar removed his ring.<ref name=\"Rizvi1988\">{{cite book|author=Akhtar Rizvi, Sayyid Saeed|title=Imamate: The vicegerency of the Holy Prophet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0f2qAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA24|year=1988|publisher=Bilal Muslim Mission of Tanzania|isbn=978-9976-956-13-9|pages=24\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"CornilleConway2010\">{{cite book|author1=Cornille, Catherine|author2=Conway, Christopher|title=Interreligious Hermeneutics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZpcNBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT124|date=1 July 2010|publisher=Wipf and Stock Publishers|isbn=978-1-63087-425-4|pages=124\u2013}}</ref> Then Muhammad observed this, and a passage of the Qur'an was sent down upon him (5:55),<ref name=\"Rizvi2014\">{{cite book|author=Hasnain Rizvi, Syed Tilmiz|title=Fazail-e-Ali ibn Abi Talib|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kx9uBgAAQBAJ&pg=RA1-PA42|date=3 February 2014|publisher=Lulu.com|isbn=978-1-304-87140-4|pages=1\u201342}}</ref> According to Shi'ites, in this verse, \"obedience is absolute and conjoined with obedience to God and his messenger\", so the person identified as ''Wali'' must be infallible.<ref name=\"mavani\">{{cite book|last1=Hamid|first1=Mavani|title=Religious Authority and Political Thought in Twelver Shi'ism|pp=68\u201373|date=2013|publisher=New York and London: Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-62440-4}}</ref>\n\n[[Abu Dhar al-Ghifari]], one of the earliest converts to Islam, was said to have related the following [[hadith|\u1e25adith]] to [[Ahmad ibn Muhammad al-Tha'labi]], the [[Sunni]] author of the ''[[Tafsir al-Thalabi]]'':{{sfnp|Shomali|2004|pp=140\u2013142}}\n<blockquote>One day, I was praying with [[Muhammad in Islam|the Prophet]] in the mosque when a beggar walked in. No one responded to his pleas. The beggar raised his hands towards the heavens and said, \"[[Allah]]! Be a witness that I came to the [[Prophet's Mosque]] and no one gave me anything.\" Imam Ali ([[Peace be upon him (Islam)|a]]) was bowing during his prayer at that time. He pointed his little finger, on which was a ring, towards the beggar who came forward and took away the ring. The incident occurred in the Prophet's presence, and he raised his face towards heaven and prayed:<blockquote>\"O Lord! my brother [[Moses in Islam|Musa]] had begged of Thee to open his breast and to make his work easy for him, to loosen the knot of his tongue so that people might understand him, and to appoint from among his relations his brother, as his ''wali'', and to strengthen his back with [[Aaron|Harun]] and to make Harun his partner in his work. O Allah! Thou said to Musa, 'We will strengthen thy arm with thy brother. No one will now have access to either of you!'<ref>{{cite quran|20|25|36|style=ref}}.</ref> O Allah! I am Muhammad and Thou hast given me distinction. Open my breast for me, make my work easy for me, and from my family appoint my brother Ali as my ''wali''. Strengthen my back with him.\"{{sfnp|Shomali|2004|pp=140\u2013142}}{{sfnp|Rizvi & al.|2006|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=0f2qAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA24 24]}}</blockquote></blockquote>\n\n==== Verse 5:67 ====\n{{main|The verse of announcement}}\n\n<blockquote>{{Cite quran|5|67| translator=    s| quote=O Messenger! deliver what has been revealed to you from your Lord; and if you do it not, then you have not delivered His message, and Allah will protect you from the people; surely Allah will not guide the unbelieving people.}}</blockquote>\n\nThis verse urges the Prophet of Islam to [[the event of Ghadir Khumm|announce Ali as his successor]] on his way from his last pilgrimage to Mecca.<ref name=\"EncyclopediaIslam\">{{cite encyclopedia|last1=Vaglieri |first1=Laura Veccia |authorlink=Laura Veccia Vaglieri |title=G\u0332h\u0332ad\u012br K\u0332h\u0332umm|encyclopedia=Encyclop\u00e6dia of Islam, Second Edition |year=2012 |accessdate=11 October 2019 |publisher=Brill Online |url=http://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-2/ghadir-khumm-SIM_2439| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n=== Verse 33:33 ===\n{{main|The verse of purification}}\n\n<blockquote>{{Cite quran|33|33| translator=    s| quote= And stay in your houses and do not display your finery like the displaying of the [[Jahiliyyah|Ignorance]] of yore; and keep up the Salah, and pay the Zakah, and obey Allah and His Messenger. Allah only desires to keep away the uncleanness from you, ''[[Ahl al-Bayt|Ahlal-Bayt]]'' (People of the House), and purify you a (thorough) purifying.      \n}}</blockquote>\n\nShi'ite commentators, along with some Sunni ones, record that the ''people of the house'' in this verse are the [[Ahl al-Kisa|Ahl al-Kis\u0101\u02be]] (People of the Mantle): Muhammad, Ali, Fatimah, Hasan and Husayn.<ref name=\"Leaman\"/><ref name=\"mavani\" /><ref>Sahih Muslim, ''Chapter of virtues of companions, section of the virtues of the Ahlul-Bayt of the Prophet,'' 1980 Edition Pub. in Saudi Arabia, Arabic version, v4, p1883, Tradition #61</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Muhammad ibn Jarir al-Tabari |title=Tafsir al-Tabari |volume=XXII |pages=5\u20137}}</ref><ref name=\"iranicaonline\">[http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/al-e-aba-the-family-of-the-cloak-i H. Algar, \"Al-E Aba,\" Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica, I/7, p. 742; an updated version is available online at http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/al-e-aba-the-family-of-the-cloak-i (accessed on 14 May 2014).]</ref><ref>\"F\u0101\u1e6dima.\" Encyclopaedia of Islam, Second Edition. Edited by: P. Bearman, Th. Bianquis, C.E. Bosworth, E. van Donzel, W.P. Heinrichs. Brill Online, 2014. Reference. 08 April 2014</ref>{{efn|see also al-Bahrani, Ghayat al-Marum, p. 126:al-Suyuti, al-Durr al-Manthur, Vol. V, p.199; Ahmad ibn Hanbal, al Musnad, Vol. I, p.331; Fakhr al-Din al-Razi, al-Tafsir al-Kabir, Vol. I, p.783; Ibn Hajar, al-Sawa'iq p.85 }}\nAccording to [[Wilferd Madelung]], \"the great majority of the reports quoted by al-Tabari in his commentary on this verse support this interpretation.\"{{efn|See Tabari, Jarir XXII, 5\u20137.}}{{efn|Madelung writes \"the verse addressed to the wives of the Prophet: 'Stay in your houses, and do not show yourselves in spectacular fashion like that of the former time of ignorance. Perform the prayer, give alms, and obey God and His Messenger. God desires only to remove defilement from you, o people of the house (ahl al-bayt)^ and to purify you (yutahhirakum) completely' (XXXIII 33). Who are the 'people of the house' here? The pronoun referring to them is in the masculine plural, while the preceding part of the verse is in the feminine plural. This change of gender has evidently contributed to the birth of various accounts of a legendary character, attaching the latter part of the verse to the five People of the Mantle ahl al-kisa: Muhammad, Ali, Fatima, Hasan and Husayn.\"<ref>{{harvnb|Madelung|1997|pp=14\u201315}}</ref>}} However, [[Ibn Kathir]], in his tafsir of the verse, says \"the [Sunni] scholars are unanimously agreed that they ([[Muhammad's wives]]) were the reason for revelation in this case&nbsp;... but others may be included by way of generalization.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Tafsir Ibn Kathir|publisher=IslamKotob|page=126}}</ref>\n\n=== Verse 42:23 ===\n{{main|The verse of Mawadda}}\n\n<blockquote>{{Cite quran|42|23| translator=    s| quote= That is of which Allah gives the good news to His servants, (to) those who believe and do good deeds. Say: I do not ask of you any reward for it but ''al-mawaddah fil-qurb\u0101'' ({{lang-ar|\u0671\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0648\u064e\u062f\u064e\u0651\u0629 \u0641\u0650\u064a \u0671\u0644\u0652\u0642\u064f\u0631\u0652\u0628\u064e\u0649}}, the love for the near relatives), and whoever earns good, We give him more of good therein; surely Allah is Forgiving, Grateful.        \n}}</blockquote>\n\nShi'ite commentators and Sunni ones like [[Al-Baydawi|Baydawi]]{{efn|See Baydawi, Anwar at-Tanzil. Vol.5 p.53<ref name=\"Momen 1985 334\">{{harvnb|Momen|1985|p=334}}</ref> }} and [[Fakhr ad-Din ar-Razi|Razi]]{{efn|See Razi, Mafatih al-Ghayb, vol. 7, pp. 273\u20135<ref name=\"Momen 1985 334\"/>}} agree that the near relatives in question are Ali, Fatimah, Hasan and Husayn.<ref>{{harvnb|Momen|1985|p=152}}</ref> Such a view is rejected by Ibn Kathir, who claims the verse refers to the [[Quraysh]], quoting [[hadith]]s from [[Sahih Bukhari]] and [[Ahmad ibn Hanbal]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Muhammad Saed Abdul-Rahman |title=The Meaning and Explanation of the Glorious Qur'an (Vol 9) |date=29 October 2009 |publisher=MSA Publication Limited|isbn=978-1-86179-667-7|page=40}}</ref> According to [[Wilferd Madelung|Madelung]] Shi'ite and Sunni sources agree that by the near relatives in this verse and other similar verses were meant the descendants of Muhammad's great-grandfather [[Hashim ibn Abd Manaf|Hashim ibn \u02bfAbd Manaf]], and of Hashim's brother [[Muttalib ibn Abd Manaf|Al-Mu\u1e6d\u1e6dalib]].<ref>{{harvnb|Madelung|1997|p=13}}</ref>{{verification needed|date=October 2016}}{{clarify|reason=Wouldn't this just be the descendants of Abd Manaf?|date=October 2016}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Islamic schools and branches]]\n* [[Muhammad in the Quran]]\n** [[Obedience verse#Shia view|Verse of Obedience]]\n* [[Al-Farooq (title)]]\n* [[Schools of Islamic theology]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|2}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |first=Wilferd |last=Madelung |authorlink=Wilferd Madelung |title=The Succession to Muhammad: A Study of the Early Caliphate |year=1997 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=978-0-521-64696-3}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Momen |first=Moojan |authorlink=Moojan Momen |title=An Introduction to Shi'i Islam |year=1985 |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |isbn=978-0-300-03531-5}}\n\n[[Category:Quran]]\n[[Category:Ali]]\n", "name_user": "Leo1pard", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ali_in_the_Quran"}
